As reported in literature, metal complexation is a common property for both CDs [35] and HEP [36]. Therefore, the effect of different metals, including Fe3+, Hg2+, Cu2+, Ca2+, Mg2+, Zn2+, Na+, K+, Ag+, Pb2+, Al3+, and Cr3+ on fluorescent N,S-CDs was evaluated. Only ferric could markedly induce fluorescence quenching as shown in Fig. 5
a. this can be attributed to static quenching as indicated by CDs aggregation in HRTEM micrographs (Fig. 4 c and d). The affinity of HEP towards Fe3+ complexation enabled reversing the Fe3+ induced aggregation upon addition of HEP (Fig. 4 e and f). Hence, N,S-CDs fluorescence was restored by further HEP addition ( Fig. S2
). Moreover, no interaction was observed between N,S-CDs and HEP as shown by comparing the emission spectra of N,S-CDs alone and in presence of increasing concentrations of HEP ( Fig. S3 ). Accordingly, a novel simple, sensitive, N,S-CDs based sensor was constructed for rapid determination of HEP without chemical reaction or derivatization and employing environmentally benign procedures. The developed sensor is based on the measurement of F/F0, where F0 and F are the fluorescence intensity of the N,S-CDs-Fe3+ before and after addition of HEP, respectively.

The proposed method was applied for determination of HEP in HEP sodium for IV and SC injection. The mean % recoveries and % RSD were calculated. The obtained results showed that the method can be applied to dosage form as mean % recoveries and % RSD were within the accepted range as shown in Table 2
                        . The selectivity of the developed N,S-CDs sensor was demonstrated by quantitation of HEP injection in presence of excipients. The influence of different interfering materials such as sodium chloride, methyl paraben, propyl paraben and benzyl alcohol were studied (
                           Fig. S7
                        ). The results indicated that the ability of the developed N,S-CDs sensor could selectively detect HEP in presence of other interfering substances which ensures the method selectivity. Compared with other methods reported in literature for HEP determination in its injection dosage form (
                           Table S2
                        ), the developed N,S-CDs sensor required neither tedious procedures nor complex instrumentation and expensive reagents.
